Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls called out:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Equivalent

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: No more WebForms event handlers (btnExport_Click).
    // ASP.NET Core uses action methods routed via HTTP verbs.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), Response.Write(), Response.End()
        // are ALL gone. Response.End() used to throw ThreadAbortException
        // internally — that entire pattern is eliminated.
        // Use FileContentResult or FileStreamResult instead.

        byte[] data = GenerateReport();

        return File(data, "text/csv", "report.csv");
        // Sets Content-Disposition automatically from the filename parameter.
        // For streaming large reports, use FileStreamResult:
        //   return File(stream, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect("/login", true) no longer exists.
        // The `endResponse: true` parameter called Thread.Abort() to stop
        // execution — .NET Core has no Thread.Abort at all (throws
        // PlatformNotSupportedException). Use early-return + RedirectResult.

        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // Or better — use the [Authorize] attribute (see below).
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Never catch ThreadAbortException in .NET Core.
        // It doesn't exist in this context. The old pattern of swallowing
        // it after Response.Redirect is unnecessary and should be deleted.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | .NET Core Replacement | Trap |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` | `Response.End()` doesn't exist; `HttpResponse.CompleteAsync()` exists but is rarely needed |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | `endResponse: true` called `Thread.Abort()` — which throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** | Thread.Abort is not supported; leftover catches silently mask real bugs |
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return File(...)` / `Content(...)` | Direct response writing bypasses middleware (compression, CORS, etc.) |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | `Response.Headers.Append(...)` | Still works but unnecessary when using `File()` result |
| WebForms event handlers | MVC action methods | No postback model exists in Core |

## Better Pattern: Use `[Authorize]`

Replace manual auth checks entirely:

```csharp
[Authorize]  // Returns 401/redirects to login scheme automatically
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        byte[] data = GenerateReport();
        return File(data, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

Configure the auth redirect in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(CookieAuthenticationDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
    .AddCookie(options =>
    {
        options.LoginPath = "/login";    // replaces manual redirect
        options.AccessDeniedPath = "/forbidden";
    });
```

**The #1 trap**: Developers port `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks unchanged — the code compiles (the type exists in `System.Threading`) but never catches anything, hiding the fact that the old `Response.Redirect` flow-control pattern is completely gone.
